value.value: A person in a clinical trial other than the subject who provides responses about the subject on their behalf, but not as an observer.
A clinical outcome assessment that is reported by someone other than the patient as if he or she is the patient.
A form of encryption where identifiable parts of personal data are replaced with unique artificial identifiers in order to de-identify the data within a specific context.
The extent to which the administration of a psychometric instrument and the data collected from that administration is accurate, repeatable, and sensitive.
The means of authenticating the robustness of clinical trial questionnaires and end result research to establish that they quantify what they were created to quantify.
Variables that cannot be represent by a number, used to describe data that fits into categories.
A variable that can be expressed with numeric values.
A radioactive compound that is administered to patients for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes.
The common rat, Rattus norvegicus, often used as an experimental organism.
The process of resource distribution that is done by chance.
A chart containing numbers, with or without duplication and arranged with no discernable pattern. This table may be used as a statistical tool for selection assignment.
The target group that is chosen via a sampling methodology created to provide an equal probability of being chosen.
The original information, collected from the primary source.
The interval of time during which subjects are to be enrolled in a clinical study.
The total number of study subjects to be collected for entry into the study to fulfill the protocol conditions.

label.value: Regulated Clinical Research and Information Management

value.value: A technical committee within Health Level 7 (HL7) that deals with regulated clinical research and information.
A rule that sets the conditions under which a repeating activity will stop.
The proposed assertion about which the study will determine to prove or disprove.
Risk that remains after risk control measures have been taken.
A negative-sense, enveloped RNA virus. The virion is variable in shape and size with an average diameter of between 120 and 300 nm.
Choices for replies to questions or instructions on patient-reported outcomes.

The process of submitting and updating summary information about the conclusions of a clinical study to a structured, publicly accessible, Web-based results database, such as the ClinicalTrials.gov results database. (clinicaltrials.gov)

The date and time that the summary information about the conclusions of the clinical study are submitted to a structured, publicly accessible, Web-based results database, such as the ClinicalTrials.gov results database. (clinicaltrials.gov)
Data that is collected after the fact, originating from subject recall or memory.
An approach to clinical trial monitoring that involves identifying, assessing, monitoring and mitigating the risks that could affect the quality or safety of a study.
A standard established by the biopharmaceutical industry to digitally identify subscribers, mitigating legal, regulatory, and other business risks associated with electronic transactions.
The aspects of medical product evaluation associated with risk to the subject/patient and the degree to which overt adverse effects can be tolerated.
A change to a previously determined sample population size for a study, following a review of blinded information during an intermediate point in the study.
A sequential representation of planned protocol events and activities that pertain to patient assessment within the study.
Additional individuals, organizations or other legal persons, if any, that have agreed with the primary sponsor to take on sponsorship responsibilities. (WHO)

A family of viruses that possess RNA-dependent DNA polymerases (reverse transcriptases) and contain two identical molecules of positive sense, single-stranded RNA of high molecular weight.  This RNA serves as a template for the synthesis of a complementary DNA, which may be integrated into the host DNA. Virions are enveloped.
A factor or condition subject to change in a clinical trial that is used to evaluate additional effects of the intervention not included in the primary outcome measure.
An information error that can be quickly and accurately fixed based on existing data on the form.
The ability of computer systems to share data with unambiguous meaning.
Any information that, in the event of re-identification, would harm a patient in terms of employability, reputation, insurability, or self-esteem or results in loss of income. (HIPAA)
An outlined set of steps that correspond to a therapeutic intervention for a clinical trial.

A noxious and unintended response to a medicinal product occurring at any dose that results in death, is life-threatening, requires inpatient hospitalization or prolongation of existing hospitalization, results in a persistent or significant disability/incapacity, or results in a congenital anomaly/birth defect.
A situation referring to a severe reaction, risk or indication against use of a treatment or device.

Information related to a serious adverse drug experience associated with use of a drug and derived from-(a) a clinical trial; (b) adverse event reports; (c) a post-approval study; (d) peer-reviewed biomedical literature; (e) data derived from the post-market REMs. [505-1(b) of FD&C Act (21 USC. 355-1(b)]
The process by which a location is monitored and assessed to ensure that the venue and staff are appropriate for clinical study work.
A virus whose genome consists of RNA.

A process of confirmation by examination and provision of objective evidence that software specifications conform to user needs and intended uses and that the particular requirements implemented through software can be consistently fulfilled.
The original information in a variety of media, which may substantiate information contained in an electronic record of the study.
Confirming the accuracy, authenticity, and thoroughness of a primary record by comparing it to original evidence and reports.
Substance defined by groups of elements that describes multi-substance materials or specifies further information on substances relevant to the description of Medicinal Products. (IDMP)

An individual person who both initiates and conducts, alone or with others, a clinical trial and under whose immediate direction the investigational product is administered to, dispensed to, or used by a subject. (FDA)
A therapy approved by a health regulatory authority and in wide use, which is considered to be the standard of care for the management of a specific disease or condition.
The determination by chance or probability.
A set of circumstances in which the study should be stopped early, keeping in mind the statistical reliability of the circumstances.
